title: For Sale:  Dan Wesson 741, .41 Magnum, 6" and 8" Barrel
postcontent: Dan Wesson 741, .41 Magnum, 6" and 8" Barrel Dan Wesson 741, .41 Magnum, 6" and 8" Barrel Classic Dan Wesson 741 Revolver, barely used, with 6" and 8" barrel, user's manual, belt buckle, patch, tool, barrel gauge, and case.  Blueing is immaculate on frame and both barrels.  Also included are two additional grips. Dan Wesson revolvers were made in USA by Dan Wesson company, founded in mid-1960s by Dan Wesson, grandson of one of the founders of famous Smith & Wesson Company. The goal of the newly founded Dan Wesson Company was to build high quality, most accurate and versatile revolvers for hunters, target shooters and self-defense. Such revolvers of modular design were designed and patented by Karl Lewis, and manufactured by DW in a wide number of models and modifications. Over the time, DW revolvers were extremely popular for target and silhouette shooting, and they still have strong, if small following in USA, despite being discontinued several years ago. DW revolvers were available in two basic frame sizes – medium (based on .357 Magnum frame size) and large (for .44 Magnum and larger cartridges), in nickel or stainless steel. Stainless steel versions of the basic models had numbers starting with “7”, i.e. DW Model 715 was the stainless steel version of the Model 15 revolver, etc.  Due to easily removable barrels and cylinders, one basic DW frame could be configured for a wide variety of calibers and barrel lengths, depending on availability of components and the user’s choice. Many DW revolvers were sold from the factory as “DW Pistol pac” kits with single frame and cylinder, along with several barrels of the same caliber but in different lengths.   DW revolvers are all-steel, double / single action guns with exposed hammers and frame-mounted separate firing pins. All springs are of coil type. Trigger parts are mounted to detachable trigger guard for simplified maintenance. 6-shot cylinder swings out to the left for ejection and reloading. Cylinder latch is built into the crane, to ensure most accurate alignment between cylinder and barrel. Grip frame is formed as a stud, which allows use of replacement grips of various sizes and configurations. Most prominent feature of all DW revolvers is interchangeable barrel system, patented by Lewis. Each barrel comes with its own separate barrel shroud, which can be had in a variety of lengths and styles. To install the barrel, one has to screw the barrel into the frame, place an appropriate shroud over it, and tighten it with the barrel nut which screws onto the muzzle of the barrel, using special wrench. Early guns (like model 12) had external barrel nut, later models had internal barrel nut, concealed inside the front part of the barrel shroud. Either type requires its own dedicated barrel nut wrench. When installing the new barrel, one must not forget to check the barrel / cylinder gap using special gauge, to ensure it is not too big, nor too small. Another important thing is proper tensioning of the barrel nut. This method virtually eliminates malfunctions common to direct impingement gas systems since hot carbon fouling and waste gases do not enter the receiver area. The MR762A1 stays cleaner, reducing heat transfer to the bolt and bolt carrier, and drastically reducing wear and tear on other critical components. The service life of all parts is increased substantially. The MR762A1 uses a barrel hammer-forged of the highest quality steel with 4 grooves, ensuring superior accuracy, even after firing thousands of rounds. The MR762A1 is produced at H&K's American facilities using both American and German-made components. This MIL-STD-1913 Picatinny type rail system allows all current accessories used on M4/M16-type weapons to be fitted to the MR series. The HK rail system can be removed without special tools by the user and ensures 100% return to zero when reinstalled. postcontent: This firearm is a used Colt Mustang Plus II built during the first era from 1986 to 1996. I bought it about a month ago on Gunbroker. I performed a take-down. It was a mess inside. I fired a round every second, dropped the mag, shoved the next one in, did the same, etc. I did this 4 times: 16 - 7 rd. magazines. The gun did not misfire one time, every trigger pull was a success. I wasn't doing a 2" group at that speed, but I did manage to keep most rds. within 7 inches of bullseye, not too shabby. The gun is used. It could be anywhere from a 20 to 30 yr old gun. You wouldn't know it from the exterior. That is well preserved. The interior shows all the usual signs of wear indicative of a gun of this age. But the gun works great.
